+William 96 I'm making a macroeconomic argument that is based on the 
principle that economic systems that incentivize work which is useful to 
society are successful whereas economic systems which fail to incentivize 
useful work, but incentivize indolence and destructive behavior are bad.  
If you reject this principle then things get ridiculous.  Somali pirates 
work extremely hard to steal from merchant vessels, can we achieve economic 
prosperity as a country by switching to a "piracy economy," where everyone 
competes for success at piracy?  The same arguments are made about why 
communism failed in the USSR, because the incentives were bad.  Why isn't 
the same standard applied to our system?  The MIT Ph.D. who decides to make 
an income in the financial services sector is doing this instead of 
starting a company that produces a product that solves a real social 
problem and employs people, if their income comes from, say, servicing 
student loan debt, then actually it translates to an effective tax on 
people who *are* doing this, which is actually the behavior that the 
economy should be incentivizing, not discouraging.

There are a lot of people in the U.S. who believe that markets *always* 
incentivize socially useful behavior, I disagree and think that the record 
is more mixed, libertarian-style market systems can incentivize behavior 
that lead to social prosperity under some conditions, but those conditions 
don't exist currently and aren't going to again.  In any case, if you 
reject the idea that economic systems should incentivize socially useful

"In the spring of 1978 Juanita Hickey (as she was then known during her 
first marriage) was a registered nurse running a nursing home in the town

engaged in his first run for the governorship.

Impressed by his candidacy, Juanita (as I’ll now call her) volunteered to 
hand out bumper stickers and signs, and first met the aspiring governor 
when he made a campaign stop at her nursing home.

“While he was there visiting, he said, ‘If you’re ever in the Little Rock 
area, please drop by our campaign office…be sure and call me when you come 
in.’”(A photograph of this first meeting exists: it shows a personable 
Juanita and a young Clinton looking like someone auditioning for a Bee Gees 
look-a-like contest.) On 25 April 1978 Juanita was in Little Rock for a 
nursing home convention held at the Camelot Hotel, and she did call him. He 
said that after all he wouldn’t be at the campaign office so “Why don’t I 
just meet you for coffee in the Camelot coffee shop?”She agreed to this, 
and also to a later call from him which proposed, since he said there were 
reporters in the coffee shop, that they meet instead in her hotel room. 

I had coffee sitting on a little table over there by the window. And it was 
a real pretty window view that looked down at the river. And he came around 
me and sort of put his arm over my shoulder to point to this little 
building. And he said that he was real interested, if he became governor, 
to restore that little building, and then all of a sudden, he turned me 
around and started kissing me…I first pushed him away…Then he tries to kiss 
me again. And the second time he tries to kiss me, he starts biting on my 
lip…He starts to bite on my top lip, and I try to pull away from him. And 
then he forces me down on the bed. And I just was very frightened…It was a 
real panicky, panicky situation. And I was even to the point where I was 
getting very noisy, you know, yelling to—you know—to please stop.

But that’s when he would press down on my right shoulder and he would bite 
on my lip. Her skirt was torn at the waist, her pantyhose ripped at the 
crotch, and the attorney general of Arkansas forced an entry. When 
everything was over with and he got up and straightened himself, and I was 
crying at the moment, and he walks to the door and calmly puts on his 
sunglasses.

And before he goes out the door he says “You’d better get some ice on 
that.”And he turned and went out the door. The advice about ice turned out 
to be sound, according to Juanita’s friend Norma Kelsey who had come along 
for the trip, who knew that a meeting with Clinton was planned, and who 
found Juanita in tears with a badly swollen lip and ripped pantyhose. 

She is one of five real-time witnesses to whom Juanita told the story while 
her injuries were still visible, the others (all of whom have testified to
